subsubsection.p:
Start with the simple equation

  8\cdot16=128\text{.}

Apply the \log_2(\phantom{x}) function to both sides of the equation to get

  \log_2(8\cdot16)=\log_2(128)\text{.}

Notice on the right side we already know the answer (i.e.the power of 2 that gives you 128)

Yes, you just discovered that

  \log_2(8\cdot16)=\log_2(8)+\log_2(16)\text{.}

In fact this property applies to all \log_{b}(x).

Consider the expression \log(8\cdot8\cdot8\cdot8).
We can use some shortcuts to write the expression in at least two different ways.

  \log(8\cdot8\cdot8\cdot8)=\log\mathopen{}\left(8^4\right)\mathclose{}

and using the last rule we discovered about the log of a product

  \log(8\cdot8\cdot8\cdot8)=\log(8)+\log(8)+\log(8)+\log(8)\text{.}

Remember that a negative exponent means reciprocal so a quotient can be rewritten as a product
\frac{Q}{P}=Q \cdot P^{-1}
Using the property of the log of a product, we can easily write a rule for the log of a quotient.
